 Gaussian emission feature centered around 8.5\nkeV, which we discuss to be due to cyclotron emission. Our results are\nconsistent with a fundamental cyclotron absorption line centered at\n${\\sim}10.2$ keV for all observed flux ranges. At the same time we rule out\nsignificant influence of the 8.5 kev Gaussian on the CRSF parameters, which are\nnot consistent with the cyclotron line energies and depths of previously\nreported flux-dependent descriptions. We also show that some continuum models\ncan lead to artificial line-like residuals in the analyzed spectra, which are\nthen misinterpreted as unphysically strong cyclotron lines. Specifically, our\nresults do not support the existence of a previously claimed additional\ncyclotron feature at ${\\sim}15$ keV. Apart from these features, we find for the\nfirst time evidence for a He-like Fe XXV emission line at ${\\sim}6.7$ keV and\nweak H-like Fe XXVI emission close to ${\\sim}7.0$ keV.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Dec 2019 21:57:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-19"}
